The recent by-elections in various parts of the country offered us a display of how the Executive showcases its role in contemporary governance. Granted, the Executive as the domicile of the security apparatus and executive muscle is traditionally powerful. 

In our time, however, this arm has rapidly grown into a monstrosity devouring the executive mandates of counterpart arms. The resultant behemoth totally dominates government and subordinates the others, reducing the majority of them to mere clerical functions. 



