Once the reviled lair of the president’s administrative nemeses, the Office of the President, for instance, has installed itself right in the centre of power as the biggest, heaviest and most devastating blunt political weapon in the land. 

The Executive’s disaffection with the Constitution of Kenya 2010 is well documented. As Kenya prepared to go into the 2010 referendum, for instance, desperate securocrats commandeered the Government Press to introduce a “national security” clawback into the draft constitution, obviously intending to throw the plebiscite into disarray. They failed, but were in no way discouraged. 






Executive autonomy 

 Afterwards, its functionaries used all opportunities to declaim their views of the constitution as inimical to effective government. 

In other words, the Executive’s perennial reason for flagrant noncompliance with the constitution is that the constitution itself is antithetical to effective administration of the country. It is the law which should comply with OP, not vice versa. 

OP’s chief grouse is that the frameworks of checks and balances, accountability and oversight by legislative and judicial arms, commissions and independent offices as well as the broad regime of rights-based and citizen-centred governance takes away executive autonomy and saddles government with onerous responsibilities. 



