OP’s theory is that good governance requires effective administration, which can only be achieved through the deployment of violence to secure citizen compliance with government policies and programmes. 

Anything short of that is insultingly deficient and unworthy of the term “government”. This notion of governance is inherently colonial, whereas the 2010 Constitution entails an intentionally radical decolonising agenda. Some policies reprise colonial terror at its most diabolical: torture, arson, forceful displacement, extrajudicial killings, severe restriction of freedoms and wanton, violent abuse. The great ministry views the country as a vast concentration camp with natives to be shouted at, hounded and battered for the sake of ‘good government’. 

This needs to be understood for a proper appreciation of the OP’s attitude of utter disaffection with the constitutional status quo. Its disdain is plain and its resistance resolute. 

Consider, therefore, the disgust that the decolonisation agenda has elicited in Government Square.  Article 4 of the Constitution locates national values and principles of governance set out in Article 10 as the foundation of our Republic. 

Article 10 declares the values as absolutely binding to everyone who wants their actions to be deemed constitutional and legitimate. Among these values, the rule of law, participation of the people, human dignity, equality, human rights, integrity, transparency and accountability must particularly gall our “colonial office” most of all. 



