Impunity 

It is starkly ironic that the rapid mutation of an already muscular OP into this all-consuming monster occurred during the term of the inaugural administration of the new constitutional dispensation. Without a doubt, the stupendous transmogrification of the OP is a reaction to the constitution. 

As government found its feet, OP recalibrated itself to overturn and neutralise all progress and gains in order to incrementally deligitimise the constitution and ultimately overthrow it. Thus would the colonial approach to administration be restored. 

This explains OP’s persistently anti-constitutional institutional posture, and its brazen propensity for official impunity. An outraged Law Society of Kenya has echoed retired Chief Justice David Maraga’s despairing lamentation of government’s impunity in disobeying court orders. 

On the other hand, the Cabinet secretary in charge of the OP has come out to embolden the system in this impunity by publicly declaring that court orders which the government does not like will simply be disregarded. 

Yet the impunity extends beyond mere noncompliance with judicial sanctions. There is a firm policy for OP to fully reconstitute itself as an extraconstitutional mandate whose objective is to restore robust executive lawlessness. 



